Title: ipfs
Witness: 8660726446ac26e01345d4a2d21f83820e8c5f3ed79e2a36601d277dbe156fcf

Below is a **complete, production‑ready blueprint** for a “micro‑IPFS paste‑bin” that can run either

* **as a WebAssembly‑enabled front‑end** (pure client‑side, e.g. on Vercel’s static hosting) **or**
* **as a Vercel serverless API** that talks to a tiny IPFS node and stores “pinned” CIDs in Supabase (or any other Postgres‑compatible DB).

The goal is to let users drop a short piece of text / a small file, get a **CID**, and have that CID **pinned** for a configurable amount of time without paying for a third‑party pinning service.

---

## 1. High‑level Architecture

```
+-------------------+          +-------------------+          +-------------------+
|   Browser (WASM) |  <---->  | Vercel Edge/API  |  <---->  | Supabase (Postgres)|
|   (js‑ipfs)       |   HTTP   | (nodejs + ipfs)   |   SQL    |   + Pin Table      |
+-------------------+          +-------------------+          +-------------------+
        ^   ^                         ^   ^                         ^
        |   |                         |   |                         |
        |   +--- LocalStorage (cache) |   +--- IPFS daemon (in‑proc)|
        |                             |                              
        +--- Optional: ipfs‑lite (Wasm)  (or remote ipfs‑cluster)    
```

| Component | What it does | Why it matters |
|-----------|--------------|----------------|
| **js‑ipfs (WASM)** | Runs a full IPFS node in the browser (WebRTC transport). | No external gateway needed for reads; can add content directly from the client. |
| **Vercel Edge Function** | Tiny Node.js process that can **pin** a CID using the same in‑proc IPFS node or by calling a remote IPFS daemon (e.g. `ipfs.infura.io`). | Serverless functions are cheap, auto‑scaled, and can keep a **pin‑list** in Supabase. |
| **Supabase** | Stores a table `pins(id, cid, expires_at, created_at, notes)`. | Guarantees persistence across cold‑starts; you can query “what should stay pinned?” on each invocation. |
| **LocalStorage / IndexedDB** | Caches recent CIDs + content on the client. | Instant read‑back without hitting the network again. |
| **Optional “pin‑service”** | If you want ultra‑reliable pins, you can forward to Pinata/ nft.storage / an IPFS‑Cluster node. | Redundancy for high‑value data. |

---

## 2. Data Model (Supabase)

```sql
create table pins (
  id          uuid default uuid_generate_v4() primary key,
  cid         text not null,
  expires_at  timestamptz not null default now() + interval '30 days',
  created_at  timestamptz not null default now(),
  notes       text
);

-- Index for fast lookup
create index on pins (cid);
```

*You can change the default TTL (`30 days`) to whatever fits your use‑case.*

---

## 3. Vercel Serverless API

### 3.1 Project layout

```
/api
   ├─ add.ts          // POST /api/add   – add a paste, pin it
   ├─ get.ts          // GET  /api/get   – fetch by CID (optional)
   ├─ purge.ts        // POST /api/purge – manual un‑pin (admin)
   └─ _ipfs.ts        // singleton IPFS node (lazy init)
supabase/
   └─ client.ts       // thin wrapper around @supabase/supabase-js
```

### 3.2 Shared IPFS singleton (`/api/_ipfs.ts`)

```ts
// api/_ipfs.ts
import { create } from 'ipfs-core';
import type { IPFS } from 'ipfs-core-types';

let ipfs: IPFS | null = null;

/**
 * Returns a **single** IPFS instance per Vercel Edge Runtime.
 * The instance lives as long as the serverless container is warm.
 */
export async function getIPFS(): Promise<IPFS> {
  if (ipfs) return ipfs;

  // Use ipfs-core (pure JS) – works in Vercel Edge (node 18+)
  ipfs = await create({
    repo: `ipfs-${process.env.VERCEL_REGION || 'global'}`, // isolate per region
    config: {
      Addresses: {
        Swarm: [], // no external swarm – we only need the repo + HTTP API
      },
      // Optional: enable the built‑in blockstore with memory+filesystem fallback
      // (Vercel Edge supports /tmp for a few MB of persistence)
      // If you need more than ~5MiB, use Supabase instead.
    },
    // Persist the blockstore in the Vercel /tmp directory (cleared on cold start)
    storageBackends: {
      // @ts-ignore – Vercel Edge provides a NodeFS implementation
      block: new (require('ipfs-repo')).Blockstore('/tmp/ipfs-blockstore')
    }
  });

  // Load any previously‑pinned CIDs from Supabase on start‑up
  const { data: pins } = await import('../supabase/client')
    .then(m => m.getSupabase())
    .from('pins')
    .select('cid')
    .neq('expires_at', null);

  if (pins) {
    for (const { cid } of pins) {
      // This will *pin* the block locally without fetching the whole DAG
      // (the block may not exist yet – pinning a missing CID is a no‑op)
      try {
        await ipfs.pin.add(cid);
      } catch (_) {
        // ignore – will be fetched lazily when requested
      }
    }
  }

  return ipfs;
}
```

> **Why use `/tmp`?**  
> Vercel Edge Functions have a tiny `/tmp` directory (up to ~2GiB) that survives across invocations while the container stays warm. It’s perfect for a **small blockstore** that keeps your most‑used pins alive without a separate DB.

### 3.3 Supabase client (`supabase/client.ts`)

```ts
// supabase/client.ts
import { createClient } from '@supabase/supabase-js';

const supabaseUrl = process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL!;
const supabaseKey = process.env.SUPABASE_SERVICE_ROLE_KEY!; // server‑side key!

export const supabase = createClient(supabaseUrl, supabaseKey);

export function getSupabase() {
  return supabase;
}
```

> **Security tip:** Use the **service role key** only on the server side (Vercel functions). Never expose it to the browser.

### 3.4 `POST /api/add` – create a paste & pin it

```ts
// api/add.ts
import type { VercelRequest, VercelResponse } from '@vercel/node';
import { getIPFS } from './_ipfs';
import { getSupabase } from '../supabase/client';

export default async function handler(req: VercelRequest, res: VercelResponse) {
  if (req.method !== 'POST') {
    return res.status(405).json({ error: 'Method not allowed' });
  }

  const { content, ttlHours = 720, notes = '' } = req.body as {
    content: string;        // plain text or base64‑encoded file
    ttlHours?: number;      // optional TTL (default 30days)
    notes?: string;
  };

  if (!content) {
    return res.status(400).json({ error: 'Missing content' });
  }

  // 1️⃣ Add to IPFS (as a UnixFS file)
  const ipfs = await getIPFS();
  const { cid } = await ipfs.add({
    content: Buffer.from(content, 'utf-8')
  });

  // 2️⃣ Pin locally (keeps the block in /tmp)
  await ipfs.pin.add(cid);

  // 3️⃣ Persist the pin in Supabase so it survives cold‑starts
  const expiresAt = new Date(Date.now() + ttlHours * 3_600_000).toISOString();
  const { error } = await getSupabase()
    .from('pins')
    .insert({
      cid: cid.toString(),
      expires_at: expiresAt,
      notes,
    });

  if (error) {
    console.error('Supabase insert error', error);
    // We still have the CID pinned locally, but we warn the client.
    return res.status(500).json({ error: 'Failed to record pin', cid: cid.toString() });
  }

  // 4️⃣ Return the public URL (you can use a Vercel rewrite to /c/:cid)
  const url = `${process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_BASE_URL}/c/${cid.toString()}`;
  return res.status(200).json({ cid: cid.toString(), url });
}
```

**Result:**  
*Client gets a CID and a short URL (`/c/<cid>`). The CID is pinned locally **and** recorded in Supabase so the next warm container will re‑pin it automatically.*

### 3.5 `GET /c/[cid]` – render a paste

Create a **dynamic route** in Next.js (or plain Vercel rewrites) that reads the CID and streams the content.

```tsx
// pages/c/[cid].tsx  (Next.js)
import { GetServerSideProps } from 'next';
import { getIPFS } from '../../api/_ipfs';
import { useEffect, useState } from 'react';
import Head from 'next/head';

type Props = { cid: string };

export const getServerSideProps: GetServerSideProps<Props> = async (ctx) => {
  const cid = ctx.params?.cid as string;
  if (!cid) return { notFound: true };
  return { props: { cid } };
};

export default function Paste({ cid }: Props) {
  const [content, setContent] = useState<string | null>(null);
  const [error, setError] = useState<string | null>(null);

  useEffect(() => {
    // Try to fetch from localStorage first (client‑side cache)
    const cached = localStorage.getItem(`paste:${cid}`);
    if (cached) {
      setContent(cached);
      return;
    }

    // Otherwise pull from IPFS (browser node)
    (async () => {
      try {
        const ipfs = await import('ipfs-core').then(m => m.create());
        const chunks = [];
        for await (const chunk of ipfs.cat(cid)) {
          chunks.push(chunk);
        }
        const text = Buffer.concat(chunks).toString('utf-8');
        setContent(text);
        localStorage.setItem(`paste:${cid}`, text);
        // Also pin locally so future reads are instant
        await ipfs.pin.add(cid);
      } catch (e: any) {
        console.error(e);
        setError(e.message ?? 'Failed to load');
      }
    })();
  }, [cid]);

  return (
    <>
      <Head>
        <title>Paste {cid.slice(0, 12)}…</title>
      </Head>

      <main style={{ maxWidth: '800px', margin: 'auto', padding: '2rem' }}>
        <h1>Paste <code>{cid}</code></h1>

        {error && <p style={{ color: 'red' }}>{error}</p>}

        {content === null && !error && <p>Loading…</p>}

        {content && (
          <pre
            style={{
              background: '#fafafa',
              padding: '1rem',
              overflowX: 'auto',
              whiteSpace: 'pre-wrap',
              wordBreak: 'break-word',
            }}
          >
            {content}
          </pre>
        )}
      </main>
    </>
  );
}
```

**Why a client‑side IPFS node?**  
*When the page loads, the browser spins up a tiny `js-ipfs` instance that can **cat** the CID directly from the network (WebRTC) or from the local blockstore (`/tmp` on the server) if the same CID was already pinned. This gives you a **zero‑cost, decentralized read path** while still letting the server provide a friendly HTML view.*

---

## 4. Client‑only WASM version (no Vercel API)

If you want a **pure static site** (e.g., hosted on GitHub Pages, Cloudflare Pages, or Vercel’s static output) that never touches a server, you can drop the Vercel API entirely and rely on **js‑ipfs in the browser** plus **Supabase as a “pin‑registry”**.

### 4.1 What changes?

| Feature | Server‑less version |
|---------|--------------------|
| **Pinning** | `js-ipfs` can **pin locally** (in IndexedDB) but cannot survive a page reload. To keep pins across sessions you store the CID in Supabase and **re‑pin on page load**. |
| **TTL enforcement** | A background script (or a tiny Cloudflare Worker) periodically removes expired rows from Supabase. |
| **Add paste** | POST directly to Supabase (via `supabase.from('pins').insert`) **and** add to IPFS via `ipfs.add`. |
| **Read paste** | Same as the Next.js page above, but the “pin‑list” is fetched from Supabase on startup. |

### 4.2 Minimal HTML/JS bundle

```html
<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="utf-8">
  <title>Micro‑IPFS Pastebin</title>
  <script type="module">
    import { create } from 'https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/ipfs-core/+esm';
    import { createClient } from 'https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/@supabase/supabase-js/+esm';

    const supabase = createClient(
      'https://YOUR-PROJECT.supabase.co',
      'PUBLIC_ANON_KEY' // you can expose anon key for reads/writes
    );

    // ---------- UI ----------
    const form = document.getElementById('form');
    const textarea = document.getElementById('content');
    const result = document.getElementById('result');

    // ---------- IPFS ----------
    const ipfs = await create();

    // Re‑pin any CIDs stored in Supabase on page load
    const { data: pins } = await supabase.from('pins').select('cid');
    if (pins) {
      for (const { cid } of pins) {
        try { await ipfs.pin.add(cid); } catch (_) {}
      }
    }

    // ---------- Submit ----------
    form.addEventListener('submit', async e => {
      e.preventDefault();
      const text = textarea.value.trim();
      if (!text) return;

      // 1️⃣ Add to IPFS
      const { cid } = await ipfs.add({ content: new TextEncoder().encode(text) });

      // 2️⃣ Pin locally
      await ipfs.pin.add(cid);

      // 3️⃣ Record in Supabase (TTL = 30 days)
      const expires_at = new Date(Date.now() + 30*24*60*60*1000).toISOString();
      const { error } = await supabase.from('pins').insert({ cid: cid.toString(), expires_at });

      if (error) console.error('Supabase error', error);

      // 4️⃣ Show link
      const url = `${location.origin}/#${cid}`;
      result.innerHTML = `<a href="${url}" target="_blank">${url}</a>`;
    });

    // ---------- Resolve hash from URL ----------
    if (location.hash) {
      const cid = location.hash.slice(1);
      const chunks = [];
      for await (const chunk of ipfs.cat(cid)) chunks.push(chunk);
      const txt = new TextDecoder().decode(Buffer.concat(chunks));
      document.body.innerHTML = `<pre>${txt}</pre>`;
    }
  </script>
</head>
<body>
  <h1>Micro‑IPFS Pastebin</h1>
  <form id="form">
    <textarea id="content" rows="8" cols="60" placeholder="Paste your text here…"></textarea><br>
    <button type="submit">Create Paste</button>
  </form>
  <p id="result"></p>
</body>
</html>
```

*Everything runs in the browser. The only external service is Supabase (which you can replace with any Postgres/SQLite).*

---

## 5. Pin‑TTL Management (Garbage‑Collect Expired Pins)

Because Vercel containers are **ephemeral**, you need a background job that:

1. **Deletes expired rows** from `pins`.
2. **Un‑pins** the corresponding CIDs from the local blockstore (optional).

### 5.1 Cloudflare Worker (or Vercel Cron Job)

```ts
// cron/purge.ts  (Vercel Serverless Cron – schedule: every 6h)
import { getSupabase } from '../supabase/client';
import { getIPFS } from '../api/_ipfs';

export default async function handler() {
  const supabase = getSupabase();

  // 1️⃣ Remove DB rows where expires_at < now()
  const { data: expired, error } = await supabase
    .from('pins')
    .delete()
    .lt('expires_at', new Date().toISOString())
    .select('cid');

  if (error) {
    console.error('DB purge error', error);
    return { statusCode: 500 };
  }

  // 2️⃣ Un‑pin from local IPFS store (if still loaded)
  const ipfs = await getIPFS();
  if (expired) {
    for (const { cid } of expired) {
      try {
        await ipfs.pin.rm(cid);
      } catch (_) {
        // Might already be gone; ignore
      }
    }
  }

  console.log(`Purged ${expired?.length ?? 0} pins`);
  return { statusCode: 200 };
}
```

*Deploy this as a Vercel “Cron Job” (Settings → Cron Jobs) or a Cloudflare Worker scheduled trigger.*

---

## 6. Security & Abuse Mitigations

| Threat | Countermeasure |
|--------|----------------|
| **Spam / huge files** | Enforce a max size on `req.body.content` (e.g., 500KB). For binary uploads, accept only base64‑encoded data and reject >1MiB. |
| **DoS on IPFS node** | Limit concurrent `add`/`cat` operations per IP (`rate-limit`). Vercel Edge functions already have a per‑instance concurrency limit. |
| **Public read‑only** | The paste view is **public** (no auth). If you need private pastes, add a `secret` column (random UUID) and require `?secret=` on fetch. |
| **Supabase abuse** | Use RLS (Row‑Level Security) to ensure only the service role can write to `pins`. The anon key can be limited to `SELECT` only. |
| **Pin‑TTL exhaustion** | Set a hard upper bound on total pins (e.g., `SELECT COUNT(*) FROM pins` < 10000) and reject new adds when the limit is reached. |

---

## 7. Deploying the Whole Stack

### 7.1 Supabase

1. Create a new project at <https://supabase.com>.
2. Run the SQL in **Section2** (pins table + index).
3. Enable **RLS** on the `pins` table, but **allow the service role** (`SUPABASE_SERVICE_ROLE_KEY`) full access.
4. Grab the **anon public key** (for the client‑only version) and the **service role key** (for Vercel functions). Store them as environment variables:

| Variable | Where |
|----------|-------|
| `NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL` | Vercel → Project Settings → Environment Variables |
| `NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY` | Vercel → (if you expose the client version) |
| `SUPABASE_SERVICE_ROLE_KEY` | Vercel → Project Settings → Environment Variables (Server‑only) |
| `NEXT_PUBLIC_BASE_URL` | e.g., `https://my‑paste.vercel.app` |

### 7.2 Vercel

1. `vercel init nextjs` (or `npm create next-app`).
2. Add the **files** from Sections3.1‑3.5.
3. Set the **Node.js version** to `18` (default) – required for Edge Functions.
4. Add a **rewrites** rule in `next.config.js` so `/c/:cid` maps to the dynamic page:

```js
// next.config.js
module.exports = {
  async rewrites() {
    return [
      { source: '/c/:cid', destination: '/c/[cid]' },
    ];
  },
};
```

5. Deploy with `vercel --prod`.

### 7.3 Optional: Remote IPFS daemon (if you want more robust pins)

If `/tmp` storage isn’t enough, you can point the Vercel function to a remote IPFS node (Infura, Pinata, or your own `ipfs-cluster`):

```ts
// api/_ipfs.ts (alternative)
import { create } from 'ipfs-http-client';

export async function getIPFS() {
  // No local node – just a thin HTTP client
  return create({ url: process.env.IPFS_API_URL! });
}
```

Remember to **pin** via the remote API (`ipfs.pin.add(cid)`) – the remote service will keep the data alive for you.

---

## 8. Full‑stack Summary (What you get)

| Piece | How it works | Where it lives |
|-------|--------------|----------------|
| **Add paste** | `POST /api/add` → `ipfs.add` → `ipfs.pin.add` → Supabase row | Vercel Edge Function |
| **Read paste** | Browser loads `/c/:cid` → client‑side `js-ipfs.cat` (or server‑side fetch) → cached in `localStorage` | Browser (WASM) |
| **Pin persistence** | Supabase `pins` table + Vercel `/tmp` blockstore (re‑loaded on warm container) | Supabase + Vercel |
| **TTL cleanup** | Cron job (`/api/purge`) runs every 6h → deletes rows & un‑pins | Vercel Cron |
| **Optional remote pinning** | Forward `pin.add` to Infura/Pinata | Remote IPFS service |
| **Client‑only mode** | All steps performed in the browser, only Supabase used for TTL list | Pure static site |

You now have a **self‑hosted, low‑cost, privacy‑first paste‑bin** that:

* Stores data **de‑centralized** on IPFS,
* Guarantees **availability** for a configurable period,
* Works **offline** (cached in the browser),
* Can be deployed **instantly** on Vercel (or any edge platform that supports Node18).

Happy hacking! 🚀

